[recv] {"type": "message_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Considering mock interfaces**\n\nI’m thinking that testing outside the library seems fine, but I’m wondering if the smart null mock of a package-private nested interface might have access issues. Should I use a public interface instead? Nested interfaces in a public class are implicitly static, but if there’s no public modifier, they might default to package-private. Also, can Mockito mock these? The error messages about `repository.findEntity()` seem unclear, and there could be potential issues if names aren't exact. My previous tests might need some re-evaluation too.\n\n**Improving assertion reliability**\n\nI’m considering ways to make assertions less brittle, especially focusing on ensuring the assertion contains \"findEntity.\" It seems the public API needs to support this, which might mean updating to public nested interfaces. Also, should I think about optimizing the `smartNull.name()` method? I should inspect the Mockito invocation's `toString` for mock name defaults; they aren't necessary but would be safer with `hasMessageContaining(\"findEntity\")`. Lastly, I might need to use the concrete class `Entity` with a non-final method to enhance compatibility.\n\n**Considering class structure**\n\nI’m thinking about whether to choose a class instead of an interface for the Repository. Initially, I had a mock with a subclass of the interface, which seems fine. Maybe I should edit the nested Entity to a public static class. Since interface methods are implicitly public, I could go with `public interface Repository` and `public static class Entity`. I also wonder if Checkstyle prefers inner classes to come after methods, but that doesn’t seem to be required here. I'll go ahead and edit the message.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_09693a7b58e56e42016a21f530ae588193b87817940dd26bdc\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"content\":[],\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAA